Lab3¶

Univariate Linear Regression on the California Housing Prices Dataset¶

1. Framing the Problem¶

The objective of this lab is to practice the implementation of linear regression models, utilizing a dataset focused on house price prediction. In addition, in order to understand and demonstrate the fundamental steps involved in machine learning workflows, specifically data handling with pandas, visualization with seaborn, model training and analysis and interpretation and insights.

2. Getting the Data¶

hyperlinking to the source California Housing Prices Dataset

import pandas as pd

2) Describe the 4 variables in the lab¶

Median Income

  • its range is from 0.499900 to 15.000100. and mean is 3.870671, standard deviation is 1.899822, indicating a moderate spread around the mean.

Population

  • its range is from 3 to 35862 (wide range). and mean is 1425.476744, standard deviation is 1132.462122, indicating that it has significant variability.

Number of Households

  • its range is from 1 to 6082 (wide range). and mean is 499.539680, standard deviation is 382.329753, indicating that it has significant variability.

Median House Value

  • its range is from 14999 to 500001 (wide range). and mean is 206855.816909, standard deviation is 115395.615874, indicating that house values vary widely.

Other issues

  • The maximum values for both population and the number of households are significantly higher than their respective means (large standard deviations). This indicates a wide dispersion of data points and suggests the presence of outliers.

7. Conclusion¶

  • goodness-of-fit: median income that model exhibits a lower mean squared error compared to those models using population and number of households. This lower MSE indicates that the median income model has a better fit, implying a more accurate prediction of median house values.

  • insights: the scatter plot visualizations and linear line reinforce the numerical findings, with the median income plot demonstrating a stronger and more defined correlation with median house value than the other variables. This observation supports the hypothesis that median income may have a more direct and significant impact on housing prices than the sheer number of people or households in an area. Moreover, the presence of outliers in the data could be influencing the model's performance. A potential refinement of the model could involve outlier removal or the application of robust regression techniques that can mitigate the impact of these extreme values.
